text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Linguistic Discrimination against London Accent%0a%0a:Author: MindeeL%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aBBC announcer faces linguistic discrimination. %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aArticle: https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/sep/29/those-who-ridiculed-my-accent-highlighted-their-ignorance-bbc-voiceover-diversity%0a%0aThe article describes the discrimination experienced by the BBC Radio announcer Russell Evans due to his London accent. In certain parts of the UK it is common for people to speak with what is known as "th-fronting". This is when people pronounce /θ/ as /f/. Evans speaks in this way, and has received numerous complaints and rude comments from listeners including "Firty, free and fousand aren't numbers I've ever heard of" - when he was announcing lottery numbers - and "I'm for free speech, but please can people speak properly?". According to BBC, they are trying to make an effort to have the way their announcers speak be representative of the entire UK, however it seems that some outspoken members of their audience have very strong opinions on what is the "correct" way to speak. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210509-020638-508990#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!London Accents vs. Received Pronunciation %0a-> - Simon_Y%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI had some friends who confuse the London accent with the received pronunciation. Received Pronunciation, or RP, is used by people who live in London, but other accents also exist there. As we discussed in class, one accent is not only determined regionally but also influenced by socioeconomic background, personal background, and more. In this case, there are multiple accents spoken in London, but the speaker is often segregated by socioeconomic status (I do not approve of classism, just trying to describe the phenomena). %0aThe accent described in the article is probably the Cockney dialect. One other feature of this accent is that the speaker pronounces [t] as [ʔ], the glottal stop. For example, the t in water is pronounced as [ʔ]. Which is quite starkly different from the RP.%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-020638-508990#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: C:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
