diff:1620525997:1619806315:=47,57c47%0a%3c #foxbegin 210509-020638-508990#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!London Accents vs. Received Pronunciation %0a%3c -> - Simon_Y%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c I had some friends who confuse the London accent with the received pronunciation. Received Pronunciation, or RP, is used by people who live in London, but other accents also exist there. As we discussed in class, one accent is not only determined regionally but also influenced by socioeconomic background, personal background, and more. In this case, there are multiple accents spoken in London, but the speaker is often segregated by socioeconomic status (I do not approve of classism, just trying to describe the phenomena). %0a%3c The accent described in the article is probably the Cockney dialect. One other feature of this accent is that the speaker pronounces [t] as [ʔ], the glottal stop. For example, the t in water is pronounced as [ʔ]. Which is quite starkly different from the RP.%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210509-020638-508990#%0a---%0a> %0a
